Session affinity, multi port services, and service versus ingress.

First, session affinity. By default, every connection to a service is load balanced independently, so the same client might hit different pods on back to back requests. For protocols where that is wrong, like long lived sessions stored in pod local memory, or sticky shopping carts, you set session affinity to client eye-pee, with a timeout. That mode hashes by the client's source address, and pins them to one pod for the timeout. It is the only affinity mode kubernetes offers. For richer stickiness, cookie based or token based, you need an ingress controller or a service mesh. One warning. When many clients sit behind one nat, like a corporate proxy, they all look like one address, so client eye-pee affinity stops helping. Use it for internal traffic, where each caller has a distinct address.

Second, multi port services. A service can expose more than one port. Each entry becomes a separate routing rule, and when there is more than one, each port must have a name. So you might name one http and another g-r-p-c, each with its own port and target port.

And third, service versus ingress. A service works at layer four. It speaks tee-see-pee and you-dee-pee ports, with a selector. It knows nothing about hostnames, paths, tee-el-ess, or h-t-t-p routing. For h-t-t-p routing, like send slash api to one service and slash static to another, with tee-el-ess on the front and a single public address, you want an ingress, or its newer cousin the gateway ay-pee-eye. An ingress is a kubernetes object that an ingress controller, like n-ginx, traffic, or istio, reads to configure an h-t-t-p proxy in front of your services.

So the layers stack up. A service is layer four. An ingress plus its controller is layer seven h-t-t-p. And a mesh adds mutual tee-el-ess and traffic shifting. But here is the takeaway. The service is the foundational primitive. Everything higher up uses services to find the pods, then adds smarter routing on top. Notebook nine covers ingress properly. On our map, this section spans the networking box, from service to ingress. The handoff from layer four to layer seven.
